summary:
I have “a demonstrated history of working in the computer software industry” as LinkedIn formulates it correctly. True as that is, it wasn’t the career path my younger one ever considered.
Out of the love of books I choose to become a librarian. I soon found out that a library is more about bringing people and information together than books alone.

At the same time my interest for Russian language was triggered by a chance encounter with a Russian dictionary. With a vague idea of combining both my library skills and Russian I started studying Slavonic studies at the University of Amsterdam.
6 years later I found myself with a degree in Russian, a working knowledge of Finnish and an American partner. 
During my studies I worked in the library of the Institute of East-European Studies, where I met the PC and computer networks. From there my career path took me via the computer departments of the University library to commercial software companies. 
It was not my knowledge of the Russian and Finnish grammar  that made me like the work in computer software industry. It’s been the translation between the library patron and his/her search for information; the defining of customers ideas into business rules and processes; enabling the specialist to work with the necessary patient information.

To balance out the machines I run and read about running a lot and stimulate others to run as well, both as coach on the track and as a colleague.
